# IMA Development Standards

## Philosophy
25-year veteran. FP-first, anti-over-engineering. "we" not "I". "Slow is smooth, smooth is fast."
Simple > Complex. Evidence > Assumptions.

## Tool Preferences
- Prefer rg (ripgrep) over grep for file search — faster, .gitignore-aware
- Prefer parameterized queries over string interpolation for SQL — always
- Never create custom FP utilities (pipe, compose, curry, custom monads) — use native patterns
- Use established libraries (lodash, date-fns, etc.) — don't reinvent

## Security (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
- SQL: parameterized queries only, never template literals or string concatenation
- WordPress: nonce verification, capability checks, prepared statements, output escaping on every edit
- Input: sanitize at boundaries (user input, external APIs)
- Output: escape appropriate to context (HTML, attribute, URL, SQL)

## Git Workflow
Trunk-based development with release branches.
- main = dev trunk
- release/* = release candidate branches
- v* tags = production releases

## Documentation
Three-tier: Active (permanent), Archive (historical), Transient (ephemeral, git-ignored).

## Serena Project Memory Standard
Treat `.goosehints`, `CLAUDE.md`, and `AGENTS.md` as source files for project
context, not as guaranteed runtime context. Serena-enabled recipes must call
Serena `initial_instructions` and load standard memories (`core`,
`conventions`, `tech_stack`, `suggested_commands`, `task_completion`) before
project-specific action. This is the first tool action at session start, before
greeting, Taskwarrior/Jira/Vestige/file discovery, or asking the user for local
paths/config. Use the `mcp-serena` skill migration workflow to convert context
files into those memories. For task-scoped work, seed the Vestige lifecycle
protocol so plans, implementation updates, review findings, resolutions, and
final closeouts stay connected by task key.

## Release Checklist
Before preparing a release:
- Review all local changes with `git status --short`, `git diff --stat`, and targeted diffs.
- Bump the repo release version in README for the overall release.
- Bump a recipe YAML `version` only when that specific recipe's behavior,
  instructions, parameters, or workflow changed. Do not bump unchanged recipes
  just because the project release advanced; per-recipe versions track when
  that recipe actually changed.
- Add a top changelog entry with Added, Changed, Fixed, and Validation sections.
- Update README/setup docs for any new workflow, extension, environment variable, or command.
- Validate all recipes with `goose recipe validate` and run YAML/syntax checks for touched scripts.
- Run `git diff --check` and verify no unrelated user changes were reverted.
- Confirm git workflow: changes originate on `main`; release branches fast-forward from `main`; production tags use `v<version>`.

## Code Style
- No comments unless WHY is non-obvious
- Pure functions for business logic, side effects at edges
- Native language patterns over custom abstractions
- Match complexity to context: CLI script != production API
